[{"id":"VR871959","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR871924.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following correctly indicates the direction of the electric field at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> and provides a valid justification?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR871959_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Two conducting plates of area <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"A\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math></span></span> are separated by a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"d\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span>, as shown. The upper plate has a net charge of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive Q\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"positive Q\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mpadded> <mo>+</mo> <mi>Q</mi> </mpadded> </math></span></span> and the lower plate has a net charge of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative Q\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"negative Q\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mpadded><mo>-</mo><mi>Q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>. Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"P\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> is located a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"s\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"s\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>s</mi> </math></span></span> above the center of the lower plate and closer to the lower plate than the upper plate. Assume the plate dimensions are very large compared to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"d\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span> and all gravitational forces are negligible.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows point P between two conducting plates that are separated by a distance d. A set of axes indicates that the positive x-direction is to the right, the positive y-direction is upward, and the positive z-direction is out of the page. The plates have their length parallel to the x axis and their width parallel to the z axis. Each plate has an area A. The upper plate has a charge of positive Q, and the lower plate has a charge of negative Q. Point P is a distance s above the center of the lower plate, in the positive y direction, and is closer to the lower plate than the upper plate.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR871924.g03.svg\" /></div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive y\"><math alttext=\"positive y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>y</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>-direction because the charges are equal and opposite.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive y\"><math alttext=\"positive y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>y</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>-direction because electric fields point away from negative charge and toward positive charge.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative y\"><math alttext=\"negative y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>-</mo><mi>y</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>-direction because Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> is farther from the positively charged plate.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative y\"><math alttext=\"negative y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>-</mo><mi>y</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>-direction because electric fields point away from positive charge and toward negative charge.</p>"],"answer":3}]